[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Description:** In Step 6, `top_risk_factors` is serialized with `json.dumps(row["top_risk_factors"])` before storing in DynamoDB (stored as a string attribute). In Step 7, the same field is passed directly as `row["top_risk_factors"]` inside a `json.dumps` call for the EventBridge Detail. This works correctly in both cases (DynamoDB gets a string, EventBridge gets the list serialized as part of the Detail JSON). However, a reader might wonder why the DynamoDB version needs explicit serialization while EventBridge doesn't. A brief comment explaining that DynamoDB doesn't natively support nested lists of dicts as a single attribute (without using a Map type) would help.
